# Braze React Native SDK

## Context

This rule applies when working with the Braze React Native SDK (`@braze/react-native-sdk`, v19.0.0). The SDK is a native bridge wrapping BrazeKit (iOS, v14.0.1) and the Braze Android SDK (v41.0.0). All SDK methods are static on a `Braze` class — the class is never instantiated.

## Critical Requirements

- The SDK **must** be initialized in native code (AppDelegate.swift / MainApplication.kt), never in JavaScript. There is no `Braze.initialize()` call.
- Always import as `import Braze from "@braze/react-native-sdk"` — it is a default export of a static class.
- Always clean up event subscriptions in `useEffect` return functions by calling `.remove()`.
- Pass `null` (not empty string) to unset user attributes.
- The `pushNotificationEvent` listener only works on Android.
- `logPurchase` takes price as a **string**, not a number.
- Use `getInitialPushPayload()` for cold-start deep links, not the deprecated `getInitialURL()`.
- Use `FeatureFlag` instance methods (`flag.getStringProperty()`) instead of deprecated static methods.

## iOS Native Initialization

Initialize Braze in `AppDelegate.swift` using `BrazeReactBridge.initBraze(_:)`. This must happen in `application(_:didFinishLaunchingWithOptions:)` before React Native loads. The `populateInitialPayload` call captures push data from cold starts — without it, `getInitialPushPayload()` always returns null in JavaScript.

<example>
```swift
import BrazeKit
import braze_react_native_sdk

@main
class AppDelegate: UIResponder, UIApplicationDelegate {
  static var braze: Braze? = nil

  func application(
    _ application: UIApplication,
    didFinishLaunchingWithOptions launchOptions: [UIApplication.LaunchOptionsKey: Any]? = nil
  ) -> Bool {
    let configuration = Braze.Configuration(
      apiKey: "<BRAZE_API_KEY>",
      endpoint: "<BRAZE_ENDPOINT>"
    )
    configuration.logger.level = .info
    configuration.push.automation = true

    let braze = BrazeReactBridge.perform(
      #selector(BrazeReactBridge.initBraze(_:)),
      with: configuration
    ).takeUnretainedValue() as! Braze
    AppDelegate.braze = braze

    if let launchOptions {
      BrazeReactUtils.sharedInstance().populateInitialPayload(
        fromLaunchOptions: launchOptions
      )
    }
    return true
  }
}
```
</example>

<example type="invalid">
Initializing Braze in JavaScript — this does not work because the SDK has no JS-side initialization API:

```typescript
// WRONG — there is no initialize() method
Braze.initialize("<API_KEY>", { endpoint: "<ENDPOINT>" });
```
</example>

## Android Native Initialization

Android uses XML-based configuration and lifecycle callbacks. Place credentials in `res/values/braze.xml`, register `BrazeActivityLifecycleCallbackListener` in `MainApplication.kt` for session tracking, and call `populateInitialPushPayloadFromIntent` in `MainActivity.kt` for cold-start push handling.

<example>
```xml
<!-- res/values/braze.xml -->
<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?>
<resources>
  <string translatable="false" name="com_braze_api_key">YOUR_API_KEY</string>
  <string translatable="false" name="com_braze_custom_endpoint">YOUR_ENDPOINT</string>
</resources>
```

```kotlin
// MainApplication.kt — session tracking
import com.braze.BrazeActivityLifecycleCallbackListener

class MainApplication : Application(), ReactApplication {
    override fun onCreate() {
        super.onCreate()
        registerActivityLifecycleCallbacks(BrazeActivityLifecycleCallbackListener())
    }
}
```

```kotlin
// MainActivity.kt — cold-start push payload capture
import com.braze.reactbridge.BrazeReactUtils

class MainActivity : ReactActivity() {
    override fun onCreate(savedInstanceState: Bundle?) {
        super.onCreate(savedInstanceState)
        BrazeReactUtils.populateInitialPushPayloadFromIntent(intent)
    }
}
```
</example>

## User Identity

Call `changeUser()` after login to associate all events and attributes with a user. Do not call it on logout — that orphans user data. Use `addAlias()` to link third-party identifiers.

<example>
```typescript
// After the user authenticates
Braze.changeUser("user-123");

// With SDK Authentication (JWT signature verified server-side)
Braze.changeUser("user-123", "jwt-signature");

// Get current user ID (null for anonymous users)
Braze.getUserId((err, userId) => console.log("User:", userId));

// Link a third-party analytics ID
Braze.addAlias("amplitude-id-456", "amplitude_id");
```
</example>

<example type="invalid">
Calling changeUser on logout creates orphaned data:

```typescript
// WRONG — do not call changeUser with empty/null to "log out"
Braze.changeUser("");
```
</example>

## Custom Events and Purchases

Event names are limited to 255 characters and cannot start with `$`. Property values support strings, numbers, booleans, Dates, nested objects, and arrays. `Date` objects are automatically converted to UNIX timestamps. Purchase `price` is a string, not a number.

<example>
```typescript
// Event with nested properties — dates auto-convert
Braze.logCustomEvent("checkout_completed", {
  total: 44.97,
  items: [{ name: "Widget", qty: 2 }],
  completed_at: new Date()
});

// Purchase — price is a STRING, currency is ISO 4217
Braze.logPurchase("premium-plan", "9.99", "USD", 1, {
  coupon: "SAVE20"
});
```
</example>

<example type="invalid">
Passing price as a number:

```typescript
// WRONG — price must be a string
Braze.logPurchase("item", 9.99, "USD", 1);
```
</example>

## User Attributes

Standard profile setters accept `null` to unset. Custom attributes auto-detect the value type. Pass `true` as the third argument to merge object attributes (only updates specified keys, preserves others).

<example>
```typescript
// Standard attributes — pass null to unset
Braze.setEmail("jane@example.com");
Braze.setEmail(null);  // Removes email from profile

// Custom attributes — type is auto-detected
Braze.setCustomUserAttribute("tier", "premium");
Braze.setCustomUserAttribute("score", 42);
Braze.setCustomUserAttribute("signup_date", new Date());

// Object merge — only updates "city", preserves "street"
Braze.setCustomUserAttribute("address", { city: "Boston" }, true);

// Increment numeric attribute (negative to decrement)
Braze.incrementCustomUserAttribute("login_count", 1);
```
</example>

<example type="invalid">
Using empty string to unset — this sets the attribute to "", not null:

```typescript
// WRONG — sets email to empty string instead of unsetting
Braze.setEmail("");
```
</example>

## Push Notifications

`requestPushPermission()` triggers the OS permission dialog. On Android 12 and below it's a no-op. For cold-start deep links, use `getInitialPushPayload()` — this requires native setup on both platforms (see native initialization sections). The `PUSH_NOTIFICATION_EVENT` listener only fires on Android.

<example>
```typescript
// Request permission with options
Braze.requestPushPermission({
  alert: true,
  badge: true,
  sound: true,
  provisional: false  // iOS: quiet authorization
});

// Handle cold-start push payload (requires native setup)
Braze.getInitialPushPayload((payload) => {
  if (payload?.url) {
    navigateToDeepLink(payload.url);
  }
});

// Real-time push listener (Android only)
const sub = Braze.addListener(
  Braze.Events.PUSH_NOTIFICATION_EVENT,
  (event) => console.log("Push:", event.title)
);
```
</example>

## In-App Messages

`subscribeToInAppMessage()` takes two arguments: a boolean for using Braze's built-in UI, and a callback. When the first argument is `true`, Braze renders the message natively and your callback receives it for logging. When `false`, you must render it yourself.

<example>
```typescript
// Let Braze display the message, listen for analytics
const sub = Braze.subscribeToInAppMessage(true, (event) => {
  const iam = event.inAppMessage;
  console.log("IAM:", iam.messageType, iam.message);
  Braze.logInAppMessageImpression(iam);
});

// Programmatic button interaction
Braze.logInAppMessageButtonClicked(inAppMessage, 0);
Braze.performInAppMessageButtonAction(inAppMessage, 0);

// Dismiss the current message
Braze.hideCurrentInAppMessage();

// Cleanup
sub?.remove();
```
</example>

## Content Cards

Content cards persist in a feed until they expire or are dismissed. Three types: `Classic`, `ImageOnly`, `Captioned`. When building custom UIs, you must manually log impressions, clicks, and dismissals — the SDK does not auto-track these.

<example>
```typescript
// Launch built-in feed UI
Braze.launchContentCards(true);

// Fetch cards for custom UI
const cards = await Braze.getContentCards();
for (const card of cards) {
  if (card.isControl) continue;  // Don't render control cards
  
  // Log analytics manually
  Braze.logContentCardImpression(card.id);
  Braze.logContentCardClicked(card.id);
}

// Listen for updates
const sub = Braze.addListener(
  Braze.Events.CONTENT_CARDS_UPDATED,
  (event) => console.log(`${event.cards.length} cards`)
);
```
</example>

## Banners

Banners are HTML content tied to named placements. The `BrazeBannerView` component auto-sizes height. Banners must be refreshed from the server before they're available. When using programmatic access, manually log impressions and clicks.

<example>
```tsx
// Simplest integration — auto-sizing
<Braze.BrazeBannerView placementID="homepage-banner" />

// Refresh banners from server (call early in app lifecycle)
Braze.requestBannersRefresh(["homepage-banner", "profile-banner"]);

// Programmatic access with typed property getters
const banner = await Braze.getBanner("homepage-banner");
if (banner) {
  const title = banner.getStringProperty("title");
  Braze.logBannerImpression("homepage-banner");
}
```
</example>

## Feature Flags

Feature flags have an `id`, `enabled` boolean, and typed properties. Use instance methods on the `FeatureFlag` object — the static methods are deprecated. Property getters return `null` if the key doesn't exist or the type doesn't match.

<example>
```typescript
const flag = await Braze.getFeatureFlag("new-checkout");
if (flag?.enabled) {
  const variant = flag.getStringProperty("variant");
  const maxItems = flag.getNumberProperty("max_items");
  const config = flag.getJSONProperty("layout_config");
  Braze.logFeatureFlagImpression("new-checkout");
}
```
</example>

<example type="invalid">
Using deprecated static methods:

```typescript
// DEPRECATED — use flag.getBooleanProperty() instead
const val = await Braze.getFeatureFlagBooleanProperty("flag-id", "key");
```
</example>

## Event Listener Cleanup

All `addListener` and `subscribeToInAppMessage` calls return a subscription with a `.remove()` method. Always clean up in `useEffect` return functions. Set up all listeners in a single `useEffect` block for organization.

<example>
```typescript
useEffect(() => {
  const iamSub = Braze.subscribeToInAppMessage(true, handleIAM);
  const ccSub = Braze.addListener(Braze.Events.CONTENT_CARDS_UPDATED, handleCards);
  const ffSub = Braze.addListener(Braze.Events.FEATURE_FLAGS_UPDATED, handleFlags);
  const authSub = Braze.addListener(Braze.Events.SDK_AUTHENTICATION_ERROR, handleAuth);

  Braze.requestBannersRefresh(["banner-1"]);

  return () => {
    iamSub?.remove();
    ccSub.remove();
    ffSub.remove();
    authSub.remove();
  };
}, []);
```
</example>

<example type="invalid">
Forgetting cleanup leads to memory leaks and duplicate handlers:

```typescript
// WRONG — no cleanup, subscriptions accumulate on re-renders
useEffect(() => {
  Braze.addListener(Braze.Events.CONTENT_CARDS_UPDATED, handleCards);
}, []);
```
</example>

## SDK Controls

Use data flush sparingly — the SDK batches automatically. `wipeData()` is destructive and disables the SDK until `enableSDK()` is called. Use it for GDPR "right to be forgotten" requests.

<example>
```typescript
Braze.requestImmediateDataFlush();  // Force flush queued data
Braze.wipeData();                    // Delete all local data, disable SDK
Braze.disableSDK();                  // Stop all tracking
Braze.enableSDK();                   // Re-enable after disable
Braze.getDeviceId((err, id) => console.log("Device:", id));
```
</example>

## Context7 MCP Integration

For AI-assisted development, connect to the Braze Docs MCP server via Context7. Add this to your IDE's MCP configuration and include `use context7` in prompts:

```json
{
  "mcpServers": {
    "context7": {
      "command": "npx",
      "args": ["-y", "@upstash/context7-mcp@latest"]
    }
  }
}
```

